<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-085-290  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 085 290.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Office  Jan 1990 v111 n1 p135(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>What's ahead for records management in the '90s? (data basemanagement systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stephens, David O.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Information technology is no longer considered a panacea forrecords management problems, but the continuing growth ofinformation needs will lead to accelerated automation and moreintegrated approaches to data-processing planning in the 1990s.andO;Increases in the volume of records and in users' needs forinformation will force many organizations to apply appropriaterecords management systems and technologies.andP;  Majormicrocomputer-based records management technologies includeautomated indexes to paper-based filing systems, computerizedrecords centers for inactive records, disaster recovery plans ondata bases, optical disk systems and computer networks.andO;Coordination of information systems planning grows increasinglyvital as top management begins to view information resources asstrategic business assets.andP;  Records managers will need to learntechnical skills to succeed in this environment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Data base management systemsData basesRecords ManagementOffice AutomationPreview of Coming YearTrends.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>